Problem Statement

You are the class monitor of Bright Future School.

Your teacher asks you to record the details of a new student who just joined your class. To keep the data organized, you decide to store their information using a C structure.

Your task is simple:

Read the new student’s name, age, and grade, store them in a structure, and display them exactly in the required format so the school database can accept it.

Input Format

The input contains three lines:

First line: student name
Second line: age of student
Third line: grade of student(a single uppercase letter (A–F))
Constraints

Name length ≤ 50
Age between 3 and 20
Grade is a single uppercase character
Output Format

Print the details exactly as follows:

Name: name_value_here

Age: age_value_here

Grade: grade_value_here

Sample Input 0

Rohan
12
A
Sample Output 0

Name: Rohan
Age: 12
Grade: A







#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <math.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
    struct Student{
        char name[51];
        int age;
        char grade;
    };
    int main(){
        struct Student s;
        fgets(s.name, 51, stdin);
        scanf("%d", &s.age);
        scanf(" %c", &s.grade);
        int i = 0;
    while (s.name[i] != '\0') {
        if (s.name[i] == '\n') {
            s.name[i] = '\0';
            break;
        }
        i++;
    }
    printf("Name: %s\n", s.name);
    printf("Age: %d\n", s.age);
    printf("Grade: %c\n", s.grade);

        
    return 0;
}








